From: Mono Gateway ASK <noreply@example.com>
Date: Sun, 26 Apr 2026 04:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] net: phy: swphy: support 10000Mbps fixed-link

The stock swphy emulator only accepts 10/100/1000 Mbps. On LS1046A
boards, the two XFI MAC nodes (1af0000.ethernet and 1af2000.ethernet)
declare:

    fixed-link {
        speed = <10000>;
        full-duplex;
    };
    phy-connection-type = "xgmii";

The NXP SDK fsl_dpaa_eth driver (drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/sdk_dpaa)
does not use phylink; it expects either a real MDIO PHY or a fixed-link.
With speed=10000, of_phy_register_fixed_link() invokes
swphy_validate_state() -> swphy_decode_speed() which returns -EINVAL,
emits "swphy: unknown speed", and the MAC probe fails:

    swphy: unknown speed
    fsl_mac: probe of 1af0000.ethernet failed with error -22
    fsl_mac: probe of 1af2000.ethernet failed with error -22
    fsl_dpa: probe of soc:fsl,dpaa:ethernet@8 failed with error -22
    fsl_dpa: probe of soc:fsl,dpaa:ethernet@9 failed with error -22

Mainline 10G ethernet generally goes through phylink+PCS, which has its
own state model, so swphy never grew a 10G entry. NXP's QorIQ-SDK-Linux
carries an equivalent change.

Add SWMII_SPEED_10000 to the speed[] table and a case for 10000 in
swphy_decode_speed(). The 10G entry uses BMSR_ESTATEN (the same bit
1000 sets) - the clause-22 MII registers cannot fully represent 10G
link state, but for fixed-link emulation only swphy_validate_state()
needs to succeed; the driver consults the fixed_phy_status struct
directly for speed/duplex/link, bypassing register synthesis.

---
--- a/drivers/net/phy/swphy.c
+++ b/drivers/net/phy/swphy.c
@@ -29,6 +29,7 @@
 	SWMII_SPEED_10 = 0,
 	SWMII_SPEED_100,
 	SWMII_SPEED_1000,
+	SWMII_SPEED_10000,
 	SWMII_DUPLEX_HALF = 0,
 	SWMII_DUPLEX_FULL,
 };
@@ -51,6 +52,14 @@
 		.lpagb = LPA_1000FULL | LPA_1000HALF,
 		.estat = ESTATUS_1000_TFULL | ESTATUS_1000_THALF,
 	},
+	[SWMII_SPEED_10000] = {
+		/* 10G has no clause-22 MII representation; advertise
+		 * the same extended-status bit as 1000 so emulation
+		 * stays self-consistent. swphy_validate_state() only
+		 * needs this entry to exist.
+		 */
+		.bmsr  = BMSR_ESTATEN,
+	},
 };
 
 static const struct swmii_regs duplex[] = {
@@ -71,6 +80,8 @@
 static int swphy_decode_speed(int speed)
 {
 	switch (speed) {
+	case 10000:
+		return SWMII_SPEED_10000;
 	case 1000:
 		return SWMII_SPEED_1000;
 	case 100:
